{{about|use of quotations and headlines to scare readers|dismissive use of quotation marks|Scare quotes}}
A '''scare-line''', '''scare-head''', or '''scare headline''' is a word or phrase that is presented (often as a [[quotation]] and as a headline or other emphasized text, such as a [[pull quote]]) to scare the reader,<ref name="Kaplan">{{cite book |last=Kaplan |first=Alice Yeager |title=Reproductions of Banality: Fascism, Literature, and French Intellectual Life |volume=36 |series=Theory and History of Literature |publisher=University of Minnesota Press |date=1986 |ISBN=9781452901497 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=fAC2Thie090C&hl=en&v=snippet&q=scare%20quotes&f=false#v=snippet&q=scare%20quotes&f=false |access-date=25 January 2017}}</ref> as part of a [[smear campaign]] against an opposing political candidate,<ref name="McWilliams">{{Citation |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=jcCrQC8rBPgC&pg=PA298 |page=298 |title=Southern California: An Island on the Land |isbn=9780879050078 |last=McWilliams |first=Carey |year=1946 |access-date=25 January 2017}}</ref> or to cause an estrangement or cause something to seem unfamiliar in a supernatural way.<ref name="Harries">{{cite book |last=Harries |first=Martin |url= https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=QWGzfQ5caI4C&lpg=PP1&vq=smear&pg=PA3#v=snippet&q=scare%20quotes&f=false |title=Scare Quotes from Shakespeare: Marx, Keynes, and the Language of Reenchantment |publisher=Stanford University Press |date=2000 |ISBN=9780804736213 |page=6 |access-date=25 January 2017}}</ref> The term '''scare quote''' is sometimes also used to refer to scare-lines that are direct quotations,<ref name="Harries" /> but more often refers today to [[Scare quotes|use of dismissive quotation marks]] around a term to imply doubt, irony, or scorn. 

== Origin of the terms ==
The terms ''scare-line'' and ''scare-head'' derive from ''[[Fear mongering|scare]]'' + ''[[headline]]''; the longer name ''scare headline'' has sometimes been used.<ref name="Sinclair 1">{{cite book |pages=91, 214, 285 |last=Sinclair |first=Upton |author-link=Upton Sinclair |title=The Brass Check: A Study of American Journalism |publisher=University of Illinois Press |date=1928 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=pZXZRxCVAZwC&q=scare-line#v=snippet&f=false}}</ref>  The ''Oxford English Dictionary'' notes the use of the shorter expressions ''scare-line'' and ''scare-head'', the latter as early as 1888.<ref>{{cite book |editor1-last=Craigie |editor1-first=W. A. |editor2-last=Onions |editor2-first=C. T. |date=1933 |title=The Oxford English Dictionary: A New English Dictionary on Historical Principles |location=Oxford |publisher=Clarendon Press}}</ref> The use of ''scare quote'' in the same sense dates back to at least 1946.<ref name="McWilliams" /> The term ''scare line'' also refers to "a means of directing fish towards the main, holding part of a net by frightening the fish into movement",<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.fishbase.org/glossary/Glossary.php?q=scare+line |title=scare line |work=[[FishBase]] |publisher=Leibniz Institute of Marine Sciences|editor1-first=Daniel |editor1-last=Pauly |editor2-first=Rainer |editor2-last=Froese |date=2017 |access-date=25 January 2017}}</ref> but the term is not well known outside of commercial fishing (and bird hunting, where a similar technique is used to flush birds into flight), so an influence on the journalism term is dubious despite a conceptual similarity. 

== In newspaper journalism ==
Scare-lining increases newspaper sales predictably, and this has been known for several generations.  [[Upton Sinclair]] wrote in ''The Brass Check: A Study of American Journalism'' (1928): "I knew for instance, sitting at my desk, just how many extra papers I could sell with a scare-line on a police scandal."<ref name="Sinclair 2">{{cite book |page=419 |last=Sinclair |first=Upton |title=The Brass Check |date=1928 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=pZXZRxCVAZwC&q=scare-line#v=snippet&f=false}}</ref>  The practice has also been criticized as manipulative and of [[Yellow journalism|questionable journalistic integrity]] since the same era.<ref name="Sinclair 1" />

== In modern women's magazines ==
[[Women's magazine]]s, especially from the early 1990s onward, have published an increasing number of "scare stories"<ref name="Blyth">{{cite book |last=Blyth |first=Myrna |author-link=Myrna Blyth |title=Spin Sisters: How the Women of the Media Sell Unhappiness and Liberalism to the Women of America |publisher=Macmillan |date=2007 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=2gO_48UAq2IC&q=scare#v=snippet&q=scare&f=false |access-date=25 January 2017 |pages=116, 120, 122–127, 136–137, 140, 299}} The block quotations are from pp. 123–124, 125, and 127, respectively.</ref> about health, most often using alarming headlines and "[[News style#Billboard|billboard]]" text that are not quotations. For example, ''[[Glamour (magazine)|Glamour]]'' magazine in the year 1990 had no health cover stories, but in 2002 had at least one scare-line in almost every issue, e.g. "It's Common, It Can Kill: Why Aren't Doctors Telling Us about This Women-only Disease?" (from the April 2002 issue).<ref name="Blyth" />{{rp|124}}  [[Myrna Blyth]], a [[Feminism|feminist]], [[Media criticism|media critic]], and former editor-in-chief of ''[[Ladies' Home Journal]]'', characterizes the trend as the selling of unhappiness and fear about health. Her 2007 book ''Spin Sisters'' observes the following, based on one-year, three-year, and ten-year studies of articles in women's magazines:<ref name="Blyth" />{{rp|123–127}}
{{quote|text=Two thirds of the articles reviewed in the [one-year] study never mentioned that the actual risks from any of these threats were extremely small, and even more important, that the alarmist views in many of the articles actually disagreed with mainstream science. ...{{paragraph break}}What women's magazines really specialize in are stories that make you afraid to cross the threshold of a hospital, trust your doctor, or take your medicine. In looking at ten years of cover lines ... one can see a dramatic acceleration of bad-doctor stories during the 1990s. ...{{paragraph break}}Women's magazines also package fear ... by "exposing" frightening and imminent threats to women, especially when it comes to health. Our survey of women's magazines found that when it comes to scare stories, the least substantiated ones were about health. In fact, over the three years' worth of stories we reviewed, 258 health stories about everything from food contamination to mercury poisoning to rare diseases earned space in America's magazines for women—many overly dependent on anecdotal evidence and devoid of any valid risk assessment. Often, a hint of conspiracy was added ("10 Urgent Health Risks Doctors Don't Tell You About") to ratchet up the fear factor....}}
She concludes that women acting as the effective gatekeepers of family health is why they have been increasingly targeted by this sort of writing and marketing,<ref name="Blyth" />{{rp|125}} often based on "confusing, [[Pseudo-science|junk-science]] statistics"<ref name="Blyth" />{{rp|122}} and the replacement of rigorous reporting with personal opinion and vague, exaggeratory implications with a lot of "wiggle room".<ref name="Blyth" />{{rp|126}}  Such articles also appear to be the leading source of unreasonable [[Vaccine controversies|fears about vaccines]]<ref name="Blyth" />{{rp|121–123}} (e.g., the [[MMR vaccine controversy|debunked but persistent idea]] that childhood vaccination causes [[autism]]).  Blyth concedes that her own former publication also ran such scare-lines, such as "Dangerous Medicine: When Cures Harm Instead of Heal", and "Foods that Can Kill".<ref name="Blyth" />{{rp|127}}

